title: For Sale/Trade:  Minty Remington 1903a3
postcontent: For sale is an EXTREMELY clean Remington 1903a3, produced in early August of 1943.WARTIME FIREARMS, LLC -- WE SHIP!!!Towards the end of WWII, Springfield contracted various other companies to produce the 1903, Remington being one of them. After the attack on Pearl Harbor, the US army demanded more 1903 rifles than the companies could produce, which led to the birth of the 03a3, a 1903 rifle made with stamped parts and a fixed weaver sight-base with improved battle sight, rather than the milled parts of a typical 03. The move by remington allowed for some 707,000+ of these rifles to be produced. Of those 707,000+ rifles, many were hand picked for their accuracy to be turned into the 1903a4 sniping rifle.This 1903a3 is in near-pristine condition. I do suspect the previous owner had ambitions to convert this into it's sniping counterpart, the 1903a4, as the standard and less-accurate two-groove barrel has been improved with a replacement four-groove barrel, and the front sight hood has been removed. This rifle does not show any signs of wear and tear, rust or pitting what-so-ever, and it is highly likely that it never actually saw combat, but remained unissued and sitting in a military stockpile until it was finally released to it's previous owner. There is a very minor surface rust imperfection on the rear-most sling hoop. The type 13 stock, which was seldom seen on war-time production 1903a3's, has the proper cartouches to prove it's originality: the circled "P" (proof) stamp on the pistol grip, the assembly markings in front of the trigger guard, and the Ordnance Wheel stamp in front of the boxed "FJA" (Lt. Col. Frank J. Atwood's inspection stamp--Remington only). This stock type was most common on rifles that were to be converted to 1903a4's but never finished.Overall, this is a great addition to any collection. It resembles a time of turmoil, when America was forced into a world war for the second time and had to scramble to arm its freshly-drafted young men. Unissued guns like these will command a premium in the future, so make your investment now and enjoy owning this sliver of American history.
